<DOCNO> AP900626-0002 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
one evening during the sixth international 
aids conference dr anthony fauci found himself surrounded by aids 
activists 
it was by his own choosing the director of the national 
institute of allergy and infectious diseases the governments top 
aids researcher was appearing at a theater as a panel member with 
other experts and activists 
compared with the days of demonstrations outside the conference 
the dialogue in the theater was a love feast 
fauci talked about placing more women and minorities in aids 
drugs tests and about greater community representation on 
scientific committees 
activist martin delaney of san franciscos project inform 
confessed that the slow pace of his own drugtesting program made 
him more sympathetic to government projects he had criticized in 
the past 
it takes a lot longer to come up with research than i thought 
it did delaney said 
despite the weeks arrests and angry confrontations such as the 
one that greeted health and human services secretary louis sullivan 
on sunday much of the talk within the scientific and activist 
communities was of conciliation 
members of the aids community had a greater role at the 
conference appearing on panels and questioning researchers at 
various sessions 
many of them are very well informed they ask some of the most 
pointed penetrating questions thats good for all of us said 
dr john bartlett who tests aids drugs at duke university 
i dont always agree with them bartlett said but if you 
judge their contributions on balance they have been important 
even those who work for agencies that often are the targets of 
criticism and demonstrations lauded the activists lobbying for 
accelerated drug testing and clinical trials 
dr susan mertins a researcher at the national cancer 
institute said she was angered by activist charges that scientists 
are not trying hard enough to fight aids but she said the protests 
also have done some good 
in the big picture they have influenced our thinking they 
have helped get things faster to the people who need it she said 
fauci himself hammered away at the theme of harmony during the 
conference 
activists bring a special insight into the disease that can 
actually be helpful in the way that we design our scientific 
approaches he said at the closing session shortly before 
protesters shouted down sullivan 
even after the noisy demonstration fauci was talking peace i 
still see it going in the right direction he said there is 
momentum for better relationships for a better give and take 
many in the aids community also spoke of the importance of 
cooperation 
pierre ludington a member of the american association of 
physicians for human rights said there has been a snowballing of 
togetherness 
people are getting tired of bashing up against each other 
said ludington who is infected with the aids virus many of us 
have learned to compromise 
but not everyone is talking compromise many members of the aids 
coalition to unleash power or act up the nationwide group that 
organized the daily demonstrations remain angry and wary of the 
scientific establishment 
i dont think one week makes for a greater level of 
cooperation said saundra johnson a member of act ups chicago 
chapter were going to keep it up until we get what we want 
the hostility and suspicion were evident even on saturday when 
many officials with the conference took part in a march billed as 
a united call to action 
conference cochairmen dr john ziegler and dr paul volberding 
appeared at the rally to voice their support 
weve made a great breakthrough ziegler said were all 
in this together 
but scattered with the applause were shouts of tokenism and 
a swelling chant of stop the profiteering 
</TEXT>
