<TEXT>
the sandinistas are suffering an 
identity crisis after their electoral defeat trying to figure out 
how to fight what they see as a rising tide of political 
conservatism backed by the us dollar 
it is a fight for their political lives and they know it 
we took power by the gun and lost it at the ballot box said 
a sandinista official who spoke on condition he not be named we 
do not know how to be a political opposition party 
victor tirado a member of the eightman sandinista national 
directorate said in a recent interview that international 
conditions have changed with the collapse of the socialist world 
and the world tendency to disarmament and solving all conflicts 
through negotiation 
as the sandinistas confront change leaders have proposed more 
grassroots participation in the partys decisions the party is now 
holding regional conventions as a prelude to a national convention 
next year at which leaders will be elected by secret ballot 
in their analysis of their defeat in the feb 25 general 
elections some sandinista leaders have admitted tactical and 
ideological mistakes and other failures such as corruption 
we need a moral renovation of sandinismo former interior 
minister tomas borge told a group of party leaders recently 
luis carrion another highranking party leader said the 
sandinistas had lost touch with peasants in some areas he also 
said the party had lost support because of its bitter quarrels with 
the roman catholic church 
a key issue is the attitude the party will assume toward the new 
government headed by president violeta barrios de chamorro 
some sandinistas like tirado say the time of confrontation has 
passed and the party should negotiate others argue for a 
continuation of the revolutionary hard line 
in the pages of the party newspaper barricada sandinista 
ideologues still cite irreconcilable class differences as 
justification for not cooperating with the new government 
what we have in power now is a bourgeoisie proyankee 
government wrote edgard orozco the idea of killing sandinismo 
is moving rapidly they are trying to kill politically and 
ideologically a series of concepts ideas and programs that surge 
as a true revolutionary identity 
the end of the military draft is seen as a major blow against 
the party since all draftees had had to undergo sandinista 
political education as well as military training 
mrs chamorro abolished the draft when she took office on april 
25 ending more than a decade of sandinista rule she announced 
last week that the army would be reduced by about half to 41000 
soldiers by aug 3 
the new government is also making changes in the educational 
system that the sandinistas see as a threat to their survival 
the us agency for international development aid will help 
pay for new school books that eliminate references to sandinista 
heroes and us imperialism according to government and us 
embassy officials 
the sandinistas thought that history began with them said 
poet pablo antonio cuadra a director of the chamorro family 
newspaper la prensa and critic of the sandinistas 
their worst damage was to the nicaraguan character he said 
they tried to impose an ideology and politicize generations they 
ruined our educational system 
cuadra says it will take years to repair the damage but 
nicaragua must be careful that it does not return to the 
exploitation of the prerevolutionary dictatorships 
we must study the experiences left by sandinismo he said 
how far can we go before freedom gives room to exploitation how 
can the state be a watchman over the economy 
</TEXT>
