<TEXT>
ranchers and farmers cut down 
nearly 18000 square miles of amazon rain forest in 1988 and 1989 
an area twice the size of new hampshire according to a government 
minister 
science and technology secretary jose goldemberg said monday 
that about 8 percent of the 2 millionsquaremile wilderness has 
been destroyed the government news agency agencia brasil reported 
earlier estimates had ranged from 5 percent to 20 percent 
goldemberg was quoted as saying that the destruction of the 
amazon was proceding at a frightening rate 
he presented the new figures at the opening of the 6th symposium 
on remote sensor tracking in manaus an amazon jungle city 3000 
miles northwest of rio de janeiro 
he said the data was obtained from brazils space research 
institute and was based on 222 satellite photographs of the rain 
forest the margin of error was 20 percent goldemberg said 
the greatest rise in devastation last year occurred in the state 
of amazonas of which manaus is the capital more than 11000 
square miles of forest were destroyed there last year according to 
the institutes figures 
most of the devastation was by farmers and ranchers who burned 
huge tracts of land for cattle grazing or farming 
