<TEXT>
the us aircraft carrier midway will return to the 
western pacific on friday for routine flight operations nine days 
after an explosion aboard killed two crewmen navy officials said 
today 
the cause of the july 20 blast which also seriously injured 
nine sailors is still under investigation said cmdr mark d 
neuhart public affairs officer for the 7th fleet 
six of the injured were airlifted last friday to the brooke army 
medical center burn unit in san antonio texas and a seventh was 
still too ill to be moved he remained in serious condition in the 
naval hospital in yokosuka along with two others in satisfactory 
condition neuhart said tuesday 
he said the midway would leave its home port at the navys 
yokosuka base at 9 am friday 
after the 67000ton ship returned to port on thursday to 
replenish emergency equipment and give the crew a rest joint 
exercises with japans maritime selfdefense force were canceled 
neuhart said 
the explosion occurred in an emergency equipment storeroom when 
a firefighting crew opened the hatch to investigate smoke navy 
officials have said the room is near steam lines carrying steam at 
850 degrees for the ships planelaunching catapult system 
rear adm henri b chase commander of the 7th fleets 
amphibious forces arrived from okinawa on saturday to lead the 
investigation neuhart said he said the damage was still being 
assessed 
the explosion led dozens of japanese opponents of the us 
military presence to demonstrate at the gate to the yokosuka base 
critics in japan the only country to experience nuclear attack 
contend the midway and other us ships routinely bring nuclear 
weapons into japan in violation of a japanese ban the navy refuses 
to confirm or deny the presence of nuclear weapons on its ships 
</TEXT>
