<TEXT>
it is prudent for americans to be concerned 
about food safety but theres no need to go overboard about it a 
senior agriculture department official says 
prudence demands that we examine every threat to the food we 
eat and the water we drink deputy secretary jack c parnell 
said that is why the department and other agencies are 
continually developing new tests to prevent harmful chemical 
residues in food from reaching consumers 
but parnell told a conference on food and nutrition here monday 
that the comments of some groups demanding tougher federal 
regulations make him wonder 
i get the feeling that the only things that would make them 
happy is if we shot down every crop duster arrested every 
toxicologist and sent every college student majoring in chemistry 
to a reeducation camp he said 
parnell said there is a better way and that the usda and other 
agencies are using it 
we will make sure that good health is promoted not by 
requiring foods to be pesticidefree but by making certain that 
levels are no greater than what is considered absolutely safe based 
on scientific measurement he said 
science isnt perfect parnell said scientists can make 
mistakes and they can miscalculate but they are light years ahead 
of rumor hysteria and passions of the moment 
parnell said irrational fears about chemicals and food safety 
could drive up the costs of farm production and lead to higher 
prices at the grocery store 
if we react carelessly without science in response to 
imagined risks and thereby needlessly increase food costs the 
poor will be the first to notice reduced buying power and higher 
nutrition costs he said 
the efficiency of farmers productivity has more than doubled 
in the last 40 years he said and chemicals have played a role in 
this american victory over hunger 
parnell who was director of the california department of food 
and agriculture before becoming usdas no 2 official last year 
said it has been american agriculture through inexpensive food 
that has helped enormously to raise our standard of living and 
that of many others around the world 
on the whole americans spend about 12 percent of their 
disposable income for food of which nearly 5 percent is for food 
eaten in restaurants and other places away from home 
by comparison he said residents of japan spend almost 20 
percent of its takehome pay for food the soviet union more than 
25 percent and china and india over half of their income 
but parnell said he has noticed there is a group of americans 
who are not always remembered in the debate about the safety of 
the nations food supply 
those are poorer americans who spend a much larger share of 
their budgets on food he said there are millions of 
americans perhaps over 30 million americans who spend over 50 
percent of their income on food 
foreign countries including poor third world nations also 
would feel the pinch parnell said 
these are more good reasons to act as quickly as the threat 
demands to the extent the danger requires but avoid alarmist 
calls for excessive or selfdefeating policies he said 
