<TEXT>
federal and state animal health authorities 
have begun a campaign to check on the possibility of mad cow 
disease in the united states a disorder that has stricken 
britains cattle industry 
the disease bovine spongiform encephalopathy or bse attacks 
the central nervous system and is fatal to cattle officials said 
monday there has been no scientific evidence to date that it is 
a human health hazard 
james w glosser administrator of the agriculture departments 
animal health and inspection service said bse is not known to 
exist in the united states 
the agency he said has barred the importation of live cattle 
from britain since july 1989 
also over 150 federal and state veterinarians constantly 
conduct field investigations of suspicious diseases and report 
their findings to us glosser said 
the national surveillance program will include usda animal 
health officials state veterinary diagnostic laboratories and iowa 
state university 
initially glosser said laboratories in at least 16 states will 
be cooperating in the program california iowa illinois indiana 
kentucky maryland michigan minnesota missouri new york ohio 
pennsylvania tennessee virginia washington and wisconsin 
glosser said additional states also have requested to be 
included so laboratory specimens may be received from other 
sources as well 
cattle affected by bse may suffer changes in temperament such 
as nervousness or aggression thus accounting for it sometimes 
being called mad cow disease 
other symptoms include abnormal posture lack of coordination 
and difficulty in rising reduced milk production loss of body 
weight despite continued appetite and eventually death 
confirmation of the disease is possible only through postmortem 
examination of the animals brain there is no test to detect the 
disease in a live animal 
