only sporadically during the exhibit for reporters at the state 
transportation department 
at one point during a demonstration session a calm female voice 
got out half a warning before the system crashed in an electronic 
screech 
eastbound santa monica freeway congested from la brea on ramp 
to hwonk 
officials insisted the system is an improvement over traffic 
advisories offered by commercial radio stations and defended 
investing in an experiment tilted to keeping people in their cars 
rather than using mass transit 
data gathered by the state transportation department from 
sensors in freeways city workers and other sources is radioed to 
the cars for display on a bosch travel pilot system the system 
uses a dashboardmounted 3inchby4inch tv screen to show maps of 
the freeway and nearby streets 
on monday the system was demonstrated on the freeway it will 
be tested in cars over the next year on a 14mile stretch of the 
freeway linking downtown to the westside 
by punching buttons drivers can zoom out for an overall picture 
or in on a few blocks they can display traffic information in text 
form on the tiny tv screen or they can listen in on messages 
broadcast from caltrans control center 
the latter seemed a likely preference for many motorists given 
the difficulty of monitoring the screen and the freeway 
simultaneously 
the transportation department known as caltrans kicked in 
900000 to see how drivers make use of the system and how they 
prefer to get their traffic messages the federal highway 
administration provided 750000 general motors corp chipped in 
25 oldsmobile 88s 
deputy us transportation secretary elaine l chao who helped 
introduce the system at a news conference said transportation 
planners must look decades ahead 
we are approaching the end of the national highway development 
system and we now have to concentrate more on alleviating 
congestion ms chao said 
a similar experiment to begin soon in the orlando fla area 
will install electronic mapping systems in 100 rental cars with 
tourist information available as part of the display 
the cars in los angeles will become part of caltrans network of 
traffic sources by feeding information back into trafficcontrol 
computers delivery and cab companies are expected to show 
interest and some testing will be done by commercial drivers after 
state employees and hired test drivers are studied 
jerry baxter caltrans los angeles chief said it provides more 
detailed information than radio traffic reports especially about 
streets that often are faster than jammed freeways 
that could encourage drivers to take alternate routes easing 
congestion he said 
ive been up in a helicopter a lot of mornings and you see the 
freeway is bumper to bumper and the parallel arterials are wide 
open baxter said 
the bosch navigation systems without the processor to overlay 
local traffic information will be on the market by years end 
priced between 3000 and 4000 on the test cars the gear totals 
nearly 10000 per vehicle 
baxter was asked if there werent a cheaper way to get 
information to drivers such as special radio frequencies like 
those available around airports other reporters questioned whether 
caltrans shouldnt be concentrating on getting drivers out of cars 
and into mass transit 
he said caltrans is also exploring all those alternatives in 
other programs 
this wont work for everybody he said but i think weve 
got to try everything we can think of 
