support legislation that would prohibit businesses from forcing 
students to view advertising as a condition of receiving donations 
the resolution did not deal specifically with channel one a 
controversial 12minute daily news program that includes two 
oneminute commercials however the program was mentioned in 
debate 
to obtain channel one schools sign a contract that loans them 
free color televisions a satellite dish and two videocassette 
recorders for the life of a contract as long as the program is 
aired in its entirety including commercials 
the resolution adopted today says that donations of the 
equipment should not be offered on the condition that students view 
advertising it urged state and federal legislation to bar the 
practice 
some delegates argued that newspapers have advertising and are 
viewed in the schools but others argued that no one was forcing 
students to read those ads or watch commercials on other television 
stations 
the operation by selection of program content could wield a 
great deal of influence on the minds of youngsters who dont have 
the option of turning to an alternative channel or turning the set 
off said sharon voliva a delegate from dolton ill the 
commercialism is much more damaging than the commercials 
the convention also approved a resolution urging congress to 
further study pesticide residues and children 
the pesticide resolution said preschool children have greater 
exposure to pesticide residues because they eat more food relative 
to their weight and consume larger quantities of fruit which can 
have a higher likelihood of pesticide contamination 
the group asked that congress clarify the environmental 
protection agencys authority on pesticides and dietary exposure 
