<TEXT>
shut away in a small room on the banks of the 
thames a group of diplomats haggled tuesday over an international 
accord to save the ozone layer 
they met through the weekend and until late tuesday preparing 
for a meeting in november of environment ministers and other 
officials from nearly 100 countries that meeting may for the first 
time impose an international ban on a group of chemicals that 
threatens the planet 
the threeday ministerial conference also will consider a 
proposal to create an international fund to help developing 
countries pay the high price for technology that could help the 
ozone layer 
conference sources said the diplomats were close to agreement on 
such a fund which the united states opposed until two weeks ago 
in small working groups they have been banging heads over how 
decisions will be made for the fund and over who will pay the 
estimated 2 billion to 7 billion bill to eliminate 
ozonedepleting chemicals 
the fund would be a milestone in green diplomacy and could 
serve as a model for future accounts that will be needed to pay for 
solving other environmental problems such as global warming 
world leaders are set to debate global warming a result of the 
socalled greenhouse effect at a november conference in geneva 
everyone is very tired said one diplomat speaking 
privately between meetings in a room at the international maritime 
organization but what we are doing has never been done before 
establishing an environmental agreement with money to back it up 
the ministers work if successful will extend and strengthen 
the montreal protocol of 1987 already considered an environmental 
watershed 
acting with unusual speed 56 nations agreed in september 1987 
to cut the use of chlorofluorocarbons or cfcs in half by 1996 
last year in the face of overwhelming scientific evidence on 
the effect of cfcs on the ozone layer 81 nations decided in 
principle to ban them by the year 2000 
in london the ministers will debate whether to move up the ban 
to 1997 and at what speed to phase out the chemicals the 12nation 
european community along with scandinavia australia and new 
zealand wants to move up the ban the united states and japan are 
opposed 
the signatories to the montreal protocol also hope to persuade 
more developing nations to sign it especially india and china 
which account for 40 percent of the world population and could be 
major cfc users 
both say they wont sign unless the rich nations help pay for 
the more expensive chemicals to replace cfcs 
cfcs used in aerosol sprays refrigerators foams and cleaning 
solvents destroy ozone 
ozone is a gas thinly sprinkled through the stratosphere that 
filters out harmful ultraviolet rays scientists say that without 
ozone life on earth would die 
higher ultraviolet radiation damages the human immune system 
causes skin cancer and cataracts harms crops and disrupts sea life 
the ministers are likely to agree to ban halons and carbon 
tetrachloride in addition to cfcs by the year 2000 both are used 
in firefighting 
scientific studies overwhelmingly show the ozone layer will not 
be fully restored unless all the severely damaging chemicals are 
banned worldwide and some of the less harmful substitutes are 
strictly controlled 
environmentalists and conference observers say the stakes extend 
beyond the meeting they say negotiations on ozone which are 
backed by a strong international consensus are a trial run for 
tougher battles looming over global warming 
</TEXT>
