<TEXT>
the vatican on tuesday ruled out public 
dissent by theologians striking at those challenging papal 
authority and the churchs ban on birth control 
saying the church has suffered serious harm from open 
criticism the congregation for the doctrine of the faith ordered 
theologians to uphold its moral teaching or keep quiet 
to succumb to the temptation of dissent is to allow the 
leaven of infidelity to the holy spirit to start to work the 
commission said in a 28page document approved by pope john paul ii 
the document was expected to draw sharp criticism from liberal 
catholics who have charged that the vatican is quietly extending 
the scope of church teachings treated as infallible and displaying 
an authoritarian attitude 
the document defended punishments meted out to dissidents in 
recent years and declared that adherence to church doctrine is not 
a matter of free speech 
it also affirmed the right of the church to speak out on issues 
of sexual morality rejecting the idea that its voice should be 
limited to economic and social issues 
west german cardinal josef ratzinger the head of the 
congregation and the popes main guardian of orthodoxy told a news 
conference the document was a response to a climate of conflict 
fomented by dissident theologians 
these include a group of 170 germanspeaking theology professors 
from four countries who publicly criticized the pope last year 
their statement known as the cologne declaration attacked john 
paul for his opposition to artificial birth control and his use of 
authority particularly his choice of conservative bishops 
ratzinger said preparation of his instruction on the ecclesial 
vocation of the theologian began before the cologne declaration 
but he said the german protest was an expression of the same 
tensions that prompted the writing of his document 
ratzinger rejected dissent as a legitimate form of expression 
describing it instead as a political ploy for power in the church 
during the popes 11year papacy several theologians have een 
punished for straying from church positions they include the rev 
hans kung of switzerland who was stripped of his right to teach 
theology in 1979 and the rev charles e curran barred from 
teaching at catholic university in washington dc in 1987 
the vatican document acknowledged theologians might in some 
cases question the timeliness the form or even the contents 
of some church teaching in that event they should try to resolve 
the differences in dialogue with bishops it said 
in cases like these the theologian should avoid turning to 
the mass media for it is not by seeking to exert the pressure 
of public opinion that one contributes to the clarification of 
doctrinal issues and renders service to the truth 
if the theologian still cannot accept the teaching he should 
keep his objections to himself the document said 
such a situation can certainly prove a difficult trial it 
said it can be a call to suffer for the truth in silence and 
prayer but with the certainty that if the truth really is at 
stake it will ultimately prevail 
asked whether theologians could publish books or articles 
espousing dissident views ratzinger said they should take their 
case to the competent forum in the church 
stressing the collaboration between theology and official church 
teaching the document noted theologians take an oath of fidelity 
binding them to present doctrine in its integrity and with full 
accuracy 
the theologian who is not disposed to think with the church 
contradicts the commitment he freely and knowingly accepted to 
teach in the name of the church it said 
the document stressed theologians must adhere not only to 
infallible pronouncements or documents infallibility means freedom 
from error in matters of faith and morals and is rarely applied 
it paraphrased from humanae vitae pope paul vis 1968 
encyclical reaffirming the church ban on contraception saying 
church doctrine also extends to that which concerns the natural 
law 
ratzingers report said the church cannot be run like a 
democracy a position voiced by the pope on several occasions 
standards of conduct appropriate to civil society or the 
workings of a democracy cannot be purely and simply applied to the 
church it said 
in the news conference ratzinger rejected the idea the church 
is a last bastion of an outdated authoritarianism 
</TEXT>
