<TEXT>
checking fees have jumped 28 percent in seven 
years with the typical holder of a regular account paying 108 a 
year according to a consumer group survey released tuesday 
the consumer federation of america said fees on regular 
noninterest checking accounts averaged 10796 while fees on 
interestpaying now accounts averaged 11139 
compared with a similar survey in 1988 regular checking account 
fees are up 67 percent while now account fees rose 64 percent 
compared with the groups first survey in 1983 regular fees are 28 
percent higher and now fees 623 percent greater 
the consumer group collected information in march from 170 banks 
and savings institutions in 16 states and the district of columbia 
comparisons between 1990 and 1988 however are based only on the 
111 institutions included in both surveys 
the nonprofit group representing 240 consumer organizations 
around the country is using the survey results in its push for 
legislation requiring banks to cash government checks for 
noncustomers and to provide lowfee accounts to the poor and the 
elderly 
sen henry metzenbaum dohio is trying to attach a provision 
requiring checkcashing to housing legislation pending on the 
senate floor the house and senate banking committees are 
considering truthinsavings bills that would require financial 
institutions to disclose fee and interest rate information in a 
uniform manner 
bankers are fighting governmentimposed lowfee accounts 
arguing that there is more than enough competition among banks to 
keep fees reasonable 
banks are businesses not public utilities and their prices 
reflect their costs of doing business with a margin for profit 
the american bankers association said in a statement 
the bankers group said 59 percent of 856 banks surveyed last 
year offered special lowfee accounts for basic checking service 
ken mceldowney executive director of consumer action a san 
francisco group said banks are competing for wealthier customers 
by offering high interest rates on certificates of deposit to 
offset the high rates banks are raising fees on smaller accounts 
he said 
in a sense low and middleincome consumers are a captive 
audience mceldowney said 
according to the survey a typical now account customer needed 
an average balance of 1180 or a minimum balance of 600 to avoid 
fees 
in calculating average fees the consumer group assumed that the 
typical account had an average balance of 400 falling to 200 
once a month it assumed 10 checks four withdrawals from automatic 
teller machines and two deposits a month as well as two bounced 
checks and one returned deposit per year 
monthly fees averaged 511 for regular checking accounts and 
596 for now accounts percheck fees averaged 27 cents for 
regular accounts and 26 cents for now accounts bounced check fees 
averaged 15 and returned deposits 485 the average interest paid 
on now accounts was 497 percent 
</TEXT>
