<TEXT>
a dramatic increase in smoking worldwide has been 
fostered by us trade policies that ignore the health problems 
associated with tobacco according to a report 
globally increasing tobacco use is responsible for almost 25 
million excessive or premature deaths per year almost 5 percent 
of all deaths said the report in wednesdays journal of the 
american medical association 
us trade policy is perpetuating the problem by trying to 
develop overseas especially in asia a market that is drying up 
at home said the report by the amas council on scientific affairs 
the reports recommendations included urging the nations 
largest group of physicians to lobby the us government to alter 
tobacco trade policies and imposing foreignlanguage health 
warning labels on cigarette packages for export 
a bill in congress and supported by the ama would require such 
labeling 
the us cigarette export association which represents 
manufacturers responsible for 98 percent of cigarette exports 
contends the united states has no business imposing its 
restrictions on other countries 
andrew copenhaver counsel to the cigarette export association 
said the united states is not resposible for the popularity of 
smoking overseas 
theres no evidence that consumption trends overseas are 
being affected by whether or not the us product is there 
copenhaver said 
the ama report adopted as ama policy in june 1989 said 
worldwide tobacco use has increased nearly 75 percent in the past 
20 years in 1988 alone us cigarette exports to asia increased 
75 percent the report said 
the tobacco industry ignoring longterm costs of medical 
care loss of productivity from tobaccoattributable morbidity and 
mortality continues to promote tobacco as an excellent cash 
crop the report said 
last month at a world conference on lung health meeting former 
us surgeon general c everett koop said smoking dropped 5 percent 
in the united states last year while american tobacco exports rose 
20 percent 
export of tobacco products is a moral outrage koop said 
koop said foreign advertising aimed at women and young people 
combined with a lack of warning labels cause many nonsmokers to 
take up the habit 
dr harvey estes jr an ama council member said the government 
wrongfully views tobacco exports as a trade issue rather than a 
health issue 
it seems irrational to advocate that we export a product that 
we know is going to cause death and disability to another segment 
of the world he said in a telephone interview monday 
but us trade officials believe tobacco is a legal commodity 
and therefore should not be unfairly restricted said timothy 
oleary spokesman for the office of the us trade representative 
its probably suitable for any given country in the world 
to decide if it wants to permit smoking but as long as smoking is 
legal then that country ought not to discriminate against us 
tobacco he said by telephone tuesday from washington 
