<TEXT>
after 55 years at the bottom of the sea 
the last us dirigible and two rare sparrowhawk scout planes were 
located in 1500 feet of chilly water by a tiny navy submarine 
the 785footlong macon was returning to moffett field about 45 
miles south of san francisco when it was damaged in a storm on 
feb 12 1935 and settled into the sea it was carrying a crew of 
83 and four sparrowhawks 
lifeboats saved 81 of the crew but the macon slid beneath the 
surface about 100 miles south of san francisco and disappeared it 
was spotted on sunday by the threeman crew of the titaniumhulled 
seacliff which had been commissioned to find the wreck 
its a delightful surprise said squadron leader henry 
miller now 87 the only macon crewman still alive 
im simply thrilled miller said in a telephone interview 
from his home in shawnee mission kan 
the dirigible which was about four times as long as the popular 
goodyear blimps went down after a tail fin snapped in heavy wind 
and rain puncturing three helium cells according to john sanders 
a spokesman at the naval postgraduate school in monterey 
recalling the accident miller said it was obvious the ship 
was a goner after it began losing altitude as the deflated tail 
section dragged the airship downward the captain sent several men 
to the nose to try to balance the ship 
when the macon went into the ocean about 15 miles offshore 
miller was one of the men on the nose 
it was just like a big old hen settling down on a nest he 
said of the crash 
sanders said searchers have always looked south of the 
lighthouse for the wreckage but apparently the macon was dragged 
north by the california undercurrent a clue discovered in the late 
1970s helped solve the puzzle 
a piece of the macon was pulled from the water by fisherman dave 
canepa and it eventually wound up hanging on the wall of a 
restaurant chris grech of the monterey bay aquarium one of a 
small group of people looking for the wreck heard about the junk 
hanging on the dining room wall and traced it back to canepa 
canepa who says he never threw any of my fishing records 
away told grech where he found the debris grech passed it on to 
the navy 
the discovery is a tremendous find for aviation museums 
said sanders only one intact sparrowhawk exists on display at the 
smithsonian institution in washington dc 
they were the most beautiful little planes i ever flew 
miller said 
the sea cliff discovered the wreck in just 15 minutes on the 
first dive pilot lt pat scanlon said scanlon said the airships 
frame was collapsed but the crew could see two sparrowhawks intact 
it was amazing said observer lt jg jerry peterson my 
heart skipped a beat when we saw it 
the macon is settled on a flat sandy bottom scanlon said with 
two of the sparrowhawks visible the third and fourth planes are 
probably buried in the sand he said 
the planes only had a range of 100 miles sanders said but the 
macon could stay aloft for days or even weeks the sparrowhawks on 
the macon were the only planes in the navy that didnt have landing 
gear they landed on trapezes suspended from the dirigible 
the macon crash followed the crash of its sibling ships the 
akron and shenandoah both of which were lost in storms the three 
crashes doomed the navys plans to expand the lighterthanair 
program 
