of the nations most generous municipal policies for the homeless 
in an effort to control a budget crisis that could leave the 
district of columbia with a 95 million budget deficit 
the council voted to stop immediately providing unlimited 
shelter to the homeless the legislation now goes to mayor marion 
barry for his approval 
the vote scaled back an initiative that had passed with more 
than 70 percent of the vote in 1984 it guaranteed overnight 
shelter for any homeless person who requested it 
the new policy authorizes the city to restrict annual spending 
for shelter limit the number of nights individuals and families 
can stay at the shelters and require people with money to help 
defray the cost of finding permanent housing for themselves 
the city was expected to spend 40 million on the homeless this 
year or about 15 million more than originally budgeted the cost 
of implementing the law has nearly tripled from 10 million in 
fiscal 1985 to 27 million in fiscal 1988 
tuesdays decision angered homeless advocates who said they 
planned to file suit against the city 
