<TEXT>
farmers and homeowners frequently use 
weedkillers that contain a key ingredient of agent orange that may 
be more harmful than previously thought scientists told a 
congressional panel tuesday 
it appears to me that there are other contaminants in 
herbicides as well as herbicides per se which have not been 
adequately evaluated for carcinogenicity in animals let alone 
studied for their effect in humans daniel thau teitelbaum a 
denver physician told a house government operations subcommittee 
teitelbaum studied industry records as part of the classaction 
lawsuit by vietnam veterans against the makers of agent orange 
in the 20 years of controversy surrounding whether the 
government should pay benefits to ailing vietnam veterans who were 
exposed to agent orange attention has focused on dioxin 
contamination 245t one of the herbicides two key ingredients 
the environmental protection agency has labeled dioxin a 
probable human carcinogen and 245t has been out of 
circulation for years 
but scientists told the subcommittee that the other key 
ingredient 24d causes cancers and other ailments linked to 
agent orange evidence shows that 24d was also contaminated with 
harmful compounds some related to dioxin according to testimony 
on the government handling of agent orange research 
the farmchemical industry says ongoing research into 24d is 
needed but that the weight of the evidence so far indicates the 
risk of harm is relatively small if it does indeed exist industry 
spokesman garry hamlin said in a telephone interview from 
indianapolis 
a socalled phenoxy herbicide 24d is sold over the counter to 
kill dandelions and other lawn weeds farmers use it against weeds 
in corn wheat rice and sorghum 
teitelbaum noting that use of 245t was first discontinued 
because of concern about birth defects said studies were needed on 
possible birth defects resulting from 24d exposure 
two national cancer institute studies have shown an increased 
risk of nonhodgkins lymphoma a rare cancer in frequent users 
of agriculture chemicals said nci researcher shelia hoar zahm 
the studies of farm workers in kansas and nebraska found that 
the risk grows or drops according to skin exposure and how soon 
after exposure the worker changed clothes 
vietnam veterans were exposed to agent orange in concentrations 
far in excess of the normal strength special adviser elmo r 
zumwalt jr has told the veterans affairs department 
the department said this year it would compensate veterans for 
