<TEXT>
wind erosion in the great plains dropped 
sharply this season because of improved moisture conditions in much 
of the region the agriculture department said tuesday 
wilson scaling chief of the departments soil conservation 
service said an estimated 78 million acres were damaged by wind 
in the 10 states that make up the great plains down 45 percent 
from 143 million acres in 198889 
the agency measures wind damage during a sevenmonth season that 
runs from november 1 through may 31 when winds are usually the 
strongest and soils the driest the survey covers 541 counties in 
the 10 states 
most of this decrease is the result of precipitation in 
colorado and kansas where land damaged from wind decreased from 
65 million acres last year to 463000 acres this year for the two 
states scaling said 
the greatest damage was in north dakota in its third year of 
severe drought he said the state reported 29 million acres 
damaged this season compared with 23 million last year and a 
record 35 million acres in 198788 
north dakota accounted for more than onethird of the total wind 
erosion in the 10state region 
kansas after setting a record with 51 million acres damaged 
last year largely due to a oneday storm that damaged nearly 48 
million acres reported only 190000 damaged this season 
the least damage was in nebraska with 130000 acres damaged 
compared with 192000 last year 
officials said the record for land damaged by wind in the great 
plains was 153 million acres in 195455 the year that the agency 
began annual records 
according to the survey the statebystate breakdown comparing 
winddamaged acres in 198990 with damage in 198889 included 
colorado 273731 and 1403655 
kansas 189600 and 5126250 
montana 1249665 and 1832025 
nebraska 130115 and 191605 
new mexico 248500 and 117950 
north dakota 2932687 and 2297681 
oklahoma 136800 and 111930 
south dakota 601830 and 678550 
texas 1668000 and 1979626 
wyoming 407550 and 552680 
