<TEXT>
peruvians lined up to buy bread gasoline and 
other essentials tuesday as presidentelect alberto fujimori 
prepared to travel to the united states to seek aid to cope with a 
deepening economic crisis 
in lima housewives stood in blocklong lines to buy bottled 
cooking gas children waited hours to buy fistsized loaves of 
bread hundreds of taxis and buses idled near the few open gas 
stations 
perus currency the inti lost value by the hour on the free 
market the inti has been devalued by 48 percent in one week and by 
23 percent since monday morning 
the shortages come five weeks before fujimori is to be sworn in 
as perus next president fujimori an agronomist who was a 
political unknown at the start of the election campaign defeated 
noted novelist mario vargas llosa in the june 10 presidential 
runoff 
on thursday fujimori is scheduled to travel to new york where 
he plans to visit the united nations to seek emergency economic aid 
to finance food imports 
he will also travel to washington to meet with officials of the 
international monetary fund world bank and interamerican 
development bank he hopes to reestablish ties with international 
lenders that were broken by his predecessor alan garcia who 
limited payments on the countrys 20 billion foreign debt 
fujimori the son of japanese immigrants will then travel on to 
tokyo for meetings with japanese leaders japan has said it is 
willing to resume loans to peru if the country can show a 
willingness to deal with its serious social and economic problems 
in lima the shortages have only added to the problems of the 
capitals 7 million residents who already suffer from daily 
blackouts severe water rationing and runaway inflation 
the general manager of petroperu the stateowned oil company 
blamed the fuel shortages on panic buying and excess demand 
petroperu is very worried by the situation pedro touzett 
told a news conference tuesday people whose gas tanks are 
normally half empty are trying to fill them up every night 
housewives who normally store one gallon of kerosene are storing 
five 
touzett added that the shortage of electricity had increased 
demand for cooking gas and gasoline to power private generators he 
said the power shortages also hampered fuel distribution because 
gas stations cannot operate their pumps and natural gas bottlers 
their machinery 
the bread industry association attributed the bread shortages to 
reduced wheat imports peru imports all but 150000 tons of the 12 
million tons of wheat the country consumes each year 
once more we beg the government to import on a bigger scale 
and to do so continuously gilberto hinojosa teves of the bread 
industry association told reporters monday 
but economists say that many imports have been reduced because 
of a lack of foreign currency 
the government has been selling silver and gold to raise money 
the central bank reserves stand at 900 million mostly gold and 
silver 
centrist politician manuel moreyra said monday that the rapid 
devaluation of the inti was due to the governments unusual 
emission of bills as well as the uncertainty before political 
change 
the countrys problems have been compounded by a severe drought 
that has cut crop production and hydroelectric power and attacks 
by maoist shining path guerrillas on power lines 
