a political target 
rep robert walker rpa a member of the house gop leadership 
urged members of congress to sign a letter declaring any increase 
in tax rates unacceptable by the end of the day 90 republicans 
more than half the 176 gop members of the house had put their 
names on the paper 
rep robert torricelli dnj said the charade is finally 
over 
the other shoe raised in the 1988 presidential campaign has 
just dropped george bush has announced that hes raising taxes 
torricelli said 
sen john breaux dla said bush had scotched an electionyear 
theme for republicans 
it removes this socalled tax and spend issue from their 
arsenal of weapons he said 
senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine said the 
president had concluded that tax increases are necessary and we 
share the presidents view 
foley added i think someone who is complaining about taxes 
being raised in the budget summit will have to complain against 
both parties and the president 
white house chief of staff john sununu tried to calm the 
republican revolt house republican whip newt gingrich of georgia 
said sununu had assured him that nothing had changed in bushs 
position on taxes the white house claims the statement doesnt 
mean anything new gingrich insisted 
deficit estimates have sharply increased since bush unveiled his 
budget in january and red ink may total more than 200 billion in 
the next fiscal year 
were not interested in whos first to mention taxes and 
whos last and who gets the blame for this and that fitzwater 
said both sides want to move in a bipartisan way to resolve this 
issue and this statement is designed to reflect that feeling 
massachusetts gov michael dukakis bushs democratic rival in 
the 1988 presidential election said he told the truth about the 
need for higher taxes and paid the price by losing the 
presidency 
mr bush did not tell the truth and were all now going to 
have to pay the price for that dukakis said in boston 
meanwhile democratic party chairman ron brown said bushs 
statement was candid and sober and gives no one comfort its no 
time for partisan gloating 
budget talks are scheduled to resume wednesday and the white 
house expressed hope for a final agreement by the august 
congressional recess 
bush issued his statement after a breakfast session with top 
congressional leaders and following a weekend of meetings between 
democrats and white house budget negotiators 
it is clear to me bush said that both the size of the 
deficit problem and the need for a package that can be enacted 
require all of the following 
he listed tax revenue increases cuts in spending for 
federal benefits as well as reductions in other domestic and 
defense programs reform of the budget process and growth 
incentives a term often used to describe a cut in the capital 
gains tax rate 
bush asked about his statement as he left a photo session said 
the written statement speaks for itself and declined to 
specifically address reporters questions about his position 
i want to see this economy grow he said i want jobs i 
want to see the deficit down and this bipartisan statement speaks 
for itself now were going on to some serious negotiation 
he hailed congressional democrats for the good faith spirit 
of the budget talks and said it was essential that these talks 
get moving 
from the outset of the budget talks bush had said that 
everything was on the table for negotiation 
until now however he had refused to say explicitly that tax 
increases must be included in the deficitreduction formula 
the white house refused to acknowledge that bush had scrapped 
his nonewtaxes pledge 
are you crazy fitzwater goodnaturedly asked reporters 
however fitzwater said bushs statement amounted to a 
refinement of his earlier remarks 
weve got to deal realistically with this problem he said 
on the other hand fitzwater said i dont think that it 
bushs statement is that big a change were still a long way 
from the final details of a settlement 
there is a general consensus among budget negotiators that they 
need to reduce the deficit by 45 billion to 60 billion in the 
fiscal year beginning oct 1 and about 400 billion to 600 billion 
over the next five years 
technically the grammrudman deficit reduction law would 
require far deeper cuts based on current revenue and spending 
projections by law the government will be forced to absorb deep 
acrosstheboard spending cuts unless the deficit is kept to 74 
billion in fiscal 1991 
