<TEXT>
nelson mandela stood before congress on 
tuesday where no black from america had ever stood not frederick 
douglass not booker t washington not web dubois not martin 
luther king jr 
his arms raised in triumph from the podium of the house of 
representatives the deputy presiden of the african national 
congress became the third heroic figure from abroad to address a 
joint meeting in these revolutionary times 
lech walesa an electrician from poland vaclav havel a 
presidentplaywright from czechoslovakia and now the 71yearold 
mandela a prisoner for 27 years in south africa 
mandela is a representative of a struggle he pointedly made 
clear that is not over 
a dedicated revolutionary who will not renounce the use of arms 
he craftily reminded his audience of american blood that has been 
shed in the cause of freedom using words known to every 
schoolchild and every member of congress 
equality liberty and the pursuit of happiness he said 
are fundamental human rights which are not only inalienable but 
must if necessary be defended with the weapons of war 
this was said by an erect trim tidy calm man in a soft 
lilting south african english that made his audience strain to hear 
before him sat washington the house the senate the cabinet 
military men led by a black general colin powell chairman of the 
joint chiefs of staff the diplomatic corps including one black 
african ambassador in a sweeping white robe 
often when dignitaries visit members of congress find other 
demands more pressing and the seats are filled by staff not this 
time 
the overflow sat in statuary hall amid the granite figures 
watching on four television sets when he finished even that 
audience applauded 
sen jesse helms rnc stayed away he had fought vigorously 
when congress overriding a veto by thenpresident reagan imposed 
sanctions on south africa to bring pressure for an end of the rigid 
system of segregation known as apartheid 
helms had said in the debate that sanctions would lead to 
everlasting tyranny 
rep william dannemeyer rcalif said he boycotted as a 
matter of principle he said mandela was more like the 1960s 
revolutionary h rap brown than martin luther king jr 
but for the 24 black members of the house the moment was 
precious 
kweisi mfume formerly frizzell gray wore a black african sash 
with stripes of red and gold over his gray business suit he is a 
democratic member of the house from baltimore 
someone else apparently a staff member brought his tiny son 
dressed in a suit and led him across the house floor by the hand 
before his address mandela met with congress blacks members 
and a handful of their white allies he thanked them for pushing 
through sanctions 
to be there to see him to have him thank members of the 
congressional black caucus makes my lifetime in politics 
worthwhile said rep charles b rangel a democrat who 
represents harlem 
during the speech a shriek a whoop went up when mandela 
ticked off the names of his american heroes 
all right people called out right on 
he named washington jefferson lincoln of course but his list 
included names not always on such lists 
john brown the firebrand abolitionist whose anger at slavery 
helped start the civil war sojourner truth the black lady 
preacher who could neither read nor write but whose words stirred 
the north frederick douglass the runaway slave who bought his own 
freedom with the earnings from his speeches against slavery marcus 
garvey the black moses and king who dreamed of freedom from 
the steps of the lincoln memorial 
none of them in their time had been honored with an invitation 
to address congress the american equivalent to knighthood 
mandela became the first black who was not a head of state to 
whom that honor was bestowed 
he said he came not as a leader but as a particle of a 
people who we know to be noble and heroic enduring multiplying 
permanent rejoicing in the expectation and knowledge that their 
humanity will be reaffirmed 
 
