<TEXT>
congressional investigators reported tuesday 
that the fate of the endangered mount graham red squirrel has 
become precarious and raised new objections to a planned 
observatory on the arizona mountaintop that is its only home 
the general accounting office the investigative arm of 
congress suggested that 1988 legislation authorizing construction 
of the 200 million observatory be changed to permit a delay while 
new studies are undertaken to weigh the impact of the installation 
on the squirrels chances for survival 
the forested site of the proposed observatory on mount graham in 
the pinaleno mountains 110 miles northeast of tucson is the 
squirrels only known habitat 
in testimony before four house environmental subcommittees 
james duffus iii natural resources director of the general 
accounting office sharply questioned the validity of a 1988 study 
by the interior departments fish and wildlife service which 
concluded that building the observatory would not pose an 
unacceptable risk to the squirrel 
duffus testified that since the wildlife services biological 
report was issued and the act approving the construction of the 
observatory was passed the status of the mount graham red 
squirrel has become more precarious 
available data suggest that squirrel numbers have dropped from 
about 215 in 1988 to between 132 and 146 in may 1990 he said 
duffus said that although the exact cause of the population 
decline in unknown biologists consulted by the gao suggest that 
reduction of the red squirrels source of food mostly spruce and 
fir tree cones is a major reason 
they contend that removing trees that produce these cones in 
order to build the astrophysical facility is not biologically 
sound he said 
the university of arizona initially sought to build a 
seventelescope facility atop the emerald and high peaks of the 
mountain 
duffus said the eventual fish and wildlife report giving a green 
light to a compromise bid to build three telescopes was flawed 
because it was based on other than biological information and 
ignored the concerns of the services own biologists 
the wildlife services regional director decided on his own that 
the universitys determination to build a worldclass facility 
outweighed the risk to the squirrel an officially endangered 
species duffus said 
we do not believe that it is appropriate for a fish and 
wildlife service official to consider nonbiological information in 
reaching an opinion that could jeopardize a speciess existence 
the gao official said we believe that biological decisions 
should be based on biological information 
sam marler director of external affairs for the service said 
later there is nothing only in what the field biologist does 
and recommendations from those staff members frequently are 
modified by more senior biologists before the regional director 
makes his decision 
marler said he had heard allegations that the decision was 
improper but i havent seen or heard anything that would suggest 
it was improper 
allan beigel a vice president of the university in washington 
for the hearing said in a statement issued in tucson the 
university believed the government witnesses had saisfactorily 
responded to the concerns raised by the gao report 
university officials will try to allay concerns of members of 
the arizona delegation who believe the observatory should be 
reassessed he said 
a joint statement from the states two senators and reps morris 
udall a democrat and john kyl a republican said until the 
biological opinion is updated the project should not proceed 
their statement noted the gao opinion that the government 
would have difficulty persuading a court that it had complied 
with all the requirements of the endangered species act 
duffus said congress now faces a policy decision 
on the one hand it can allow construction of the observatory to 
continue as planned he said 
but he said it can also order the wildlife service to update its 
opinion in light of the squirrels precarious situation and 
concerns over the process used to arrive at the original opinion 
this may require additional legislation to hold construction 
in abeyance until a new biological opinion is rendered he said 
