<TEXT>
in spite of the imperfections americans 
generally tolerate their systems of governance and banking calming 
their occasional outrage by considering the alternatives 
those alternatives generally are worse than what already exists 
defects and all but sometimes it is hard to accept that verdict 
the systems are forever being tested and so therefore is the 
patience of americans 
the latest outrage is expressed by representatives of 37 states 
and the district of columbia who will see a net transfer of wealth 
from their economies to those with the biggest savings and loan 
collapses 
in the abstract the outrage is muted this is one great 
country it is reasoned and if the worst of the collapses were 
concentrated in just 13 states it is still a national issue to be 
dealt with by all the people 
it is when the numbers the specific dollar amounts are 
detailed and then broadast as they are now that the muted outrage 
is expressed in a great roar this happens for instance when 
residents in certain states stand to lose 1000 each 
it is then that acceptance breaks down and questions and threats 
begin why asks connecticut should our people lose 1000 each to 
send money to texans who will benefit by several times that amount 
why should areas of the country whose savings and loan 
associations played by the rules and kept their institutions 
solvent have to ship money to those areas in which sampls squandered 
their funds on foolish investment schemes 
alas that is the way the system works a system that appears to 
be filled with injustices but which experience suggests is still 
second to none yes outrages abound 
in the 1970s you may recall the nation humiliated its savers 
the saltoftheearth types who played by the rules who lived 
within their limits and tried to put a few dollars in the bank for 
a rainy day 
for whatever reasons it might have been fiscal and monetary 
stupidity the money saved in the bank was thrown away 
perhaps stolen would better describe what happened to it 
because inflation raged and because banks paid out in interest 
far less than was taken away by inflation the buying power of 
savers deteriorated every day 
meanwhile those who borrowed and bought goods with the money of 
savers enjoyed tremendous appreciation in value they enjoyed the 
good life with the money took tax deductions and repaid the savers 
with cheaper dollars 
the examples are myriad and they exist right now 
the young couple who postponed buying a house for the past 
decade just waiting for prices to stabilize 
now that they have the money to buy some lenders who had been 
throwing money around are stiffening their terms because they made 
so many bad loans in the past 
the smallbusiness person who took the slow but sure and steady 
course who proved his financial reliability by foregoing the 
wildly expansive course taken by his competitor 
now his credit line is shrinking because the bank made so many 
bad loans such as to his competitor that it has decided to assume 
a more conservative lending policy 
the young worker who is paying increasingly higher 
contributions to the social security system not simply to finance 
his own retirement but to make possible the retirements of the 
generation before 
anyone can cite specific personal examples especially when 
insurance or taxes are involved they can rage against the 
injustice threaten legal action demand reform but then somehow 
they learn to live with it 
it may not be fair but it is the system a very imperfect one 
always in need of fixing 
</TEXT>
