its a little different from his usual work which is writing 
scores for films hes done more than 80 or collecting oscars 
for his music nominated 18 times he owns four oscars which go 
nicely with his 20 grammy awards 
a flutist and pianist mancini now 66 began writing music 
arrangements when he was 14 he was inspired three years earlier 
when his father took him to pittsburgh to see the crusades a 
cecil b demille extravaganza 
that was the first score that i ever heard with a large 
orchestra he says and thats what kind of stuck in my head in 
all those early years i always had that writing for film 
in the back of my mind 
his first hollywood effort in the early 50s was for a scene 
in an abbott and costello epic lost in alaska he had studied 
composition theory and harmony and all that and arranged for big 
bands 
but nobody taught him to write for films that small omission 
from his education didnt bother him he says you had no choice 
but then i didnt want any choice i just wanted to work 
such onthejob training can be dicey film music has to convey 
the moment and be precisely timed right down to the nanosecond 
this may lead some to think of a hollywood composer as an ulcer 
with a stopwatch 
but it would do no good for the rousing chase music of one scene 
to keep going into the next scenes seduction attempt at least in 
most cases 
mancini insists that such problems are small 
sure he says you make mistakes in your timing and all of a 
sudden youve got 10 bars too many because you skipped some time 
or you dont have enough but you go in and fix it 
such errors usually are caught before the musicians go to work 
in the soundstage he adds he didnt say what happens if the error 
isnt caught but when was the last time you saw a seduction scene 
with chase music 
