<TEXT>
poland held municipal elections may 27 to create 
independent local governments free of communist party control here 
is an account of problems one town encountered as its new council 
began restoring democratic rule 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
marek lach knew the treasury was 
empty when he won a council seat but another truth awaited him 
the mayor had bought cars for himself and four other people with 
the towns money 
mayor zbigniew jarzebski a communist party holdover walked out 
june 12 when lach began reading a report about the cars at the 
second meeting of the new freely elected council in podkowa lesna 
16 miles west of warsaw 
lachs voice rose as he described how six months earlier 
jarzebski approved the purchase of cars for himself the director 
of a local museum and three physicians in the town 
jarzebski will be removed as soon as a new mayor can be found 
the council postponed a decision on what to do about the cars 
the 2323 councils chosen may 27 by polands first fully 
democratic elections in 50 years are supposed to restore autonomy 
to local government which has been an arm of the 
communistcontrolled central administration 
like the 9monthold national government led by solidarity the 
new councils find empty coffers and a mountain of problems left 
behind by the old regimes 
podkowa lesna is a relatively affluent suburb of warsaw 
population about 2500 but many of its streets are unpaved 
residents live in brick houses set amongst pine birch and oak 
trees there is a small food store a pharmacy and a news stand 
but little other commerce and no high school 
voters in podkowa lesna elected the solidarity citizens 
committee candidates and the new council of 15 members took office 
june 6 it chose committees on finance planning and social 
services and appointed several members to investigate the towns 
situation 
as its first fiscal act the council appropriated 800000 zlotys 
84 to send eight poor children to summer camp 
the council has yet to determine how much money it has how much 
it will need or how much warsaw will provide under the new rules 
most funds for local government must be raised by the communities 
themselves 
well need to find a gold mine or an oil well to pay all the 
towns bills said joanna walc editor of gazeta podkowianska 
the biweekly newspaper 
marek kobosko head of the councils economic committee hopes 
podkowa lesna will be able to form companies and make money by 
operating them but acknowledges taxes will have to be raised 
where the money will come from may be a problem but the council 
is fairly clear on how it should be spent 
adequate police protection is a major priority 
the three police officers who staff the towns tworoom station 
go home at the end of the day leaving podkowa lesna unprotected 
overnight 
breakins and other theft have increased 105 percent this year 
from 1989 police say one reason is loss of income under the 
freemarket economic reform plan put into effect by the national 
government jan 1 
jan jedzrejewski the local commander wants to increase the 
number of officers but the size of the force is determined by the 
interior ministry based on population residents say the town 
needs more police because it is spread out 
where to put the station is the most immediate problem it now 
is in a private home the communists expropriated in 1948 but the 
original owners are reclaiming the property as have the owners of 
another house in which the post office is located 
the council may move the police to the municipal building which 
is expected to have extra space when unneeded bureaucrats are 
dismissed 
podkowa as residents call the town also needs money to run its 
elementary school improve the sewers and expand the telephone 
system about 600 people without telephones want them and there 
are not enough repairmen to keep the existing lines in working 
order 
lach said the council will examine land sales and distribution 
under former town governments to make sure friends of officials did 
not benefit from special deals 
there also is the matter of a building and repair business that 
is run by the town administration and has more people working in 
its offices than in production 
the last 40 years changed the whole structure and values of 
the town and now we have to create them anew said councilman 
kazimierz glowacki 
</TEXT>
