<TEXT>
in the 1950s james stewart turned mean 
romantic comedies were out thrillers and westerns were in the 
boynextdoor got nasty in bend of the river spied on his 
neighbors in rear window and almost lost his mind in 
vertigo and the naked spur 
but at the start of the decade at the same time he starred in 
the tough western winchester 73 stewart gave the public one 
more look at mr nice guy elwood p dowd in harvey 
elwood is in his early 40s and shares a house with his older 
sister veta and niece myrtle mae he is the most considerate of 
men forever holding doors open and offering invitations for 
dinner a penchant for martinis his only vice 
why is he so happy according to elwood he was walking down the 
street one evening when he encountered a large white rabbit leaning 
against a lamppost and the two became instant soulmates 
elwood has no job a large inheritance took care of that and 
no girl but always has a wonderful time thanks to the towering 
and invisible presence of his dear friend harvey 
is he alone veta is asked well theres two schools of 
thought sir she responds 
now elwood wants everybody to meet harvey much to the 
unhappiness of his relatives why cant we live like other 
people complains myrtle mae who seeks a man but wont bring 
anyone to the house fearing the inevitable introduction to the 
unseen rabbit 
veta is more sympathetic but when she invites wealthy aunt 
ethel for an afternoon tea party elwood quickly clears the room as 
he brings his special friend around to meet the guests 
and thats the last straw veta attempts to have elwood placed 
in a sanitarium but the psychiatrist mistakenly believes she is 
the crazy one and has her carried off to a soundproof chamber 
boasts elwood ive wrestled with reality for 35 years doctor 
and im happy to say ive finally won it 
everything works out fine of course veta is released myrtle 
mae gets a bpyfriend the psychiatrist falls for his nurse and 
elwood who makes believers out of almost everybody strolls 
amiably into the sunset harvey by his side 
elwood is one of the actors most popular roles stewart first 
portrayed him on stage as a summer replacement for frank fay in 
1947 and was offered the part for the film version of mary chases 
pulitzer prizewinning play 
harvey brought him an academy award nomination josephine 
hull won an oscar for best supporting actress as veta and stewart 
would continue to play elwood in theater revivals but the film 
and its gentle message about whos sane and whos not has aged 
badly home viewers may be interested however in stewarts 
observations given in a special introduction to the black and white 
video 
in this world you must be oh so smart or oh so pleasant 
elwood says of his unflappable geniality and that sums up this 
sweet bland comedy even stewart has said his portrayal was too 
nice he brought out more haunting aspects in later appearances 
including a 1972 television production 
