<TEXT>
john eliot gardiner has such a high opinion of 
mozarts opera idomeneo that he decided not to put it on stage 
this summer 
i didnt want to be distracted quite honestly by the dangers 
of a producer who had a completely different idea of the score from 
mine because there is so much musical richness and explicitness in 
the score gardiner said 
instead he led three concert performances of idomeneo at 
the south bank center last month to kick off a sixyear 
sevenopera mozart recording project for the english baroque 
soloists and monteverdi choir 
it was an electrifying beginning gardiners high dramatic 
immaculately detailed reading was supported by silken performances 
on original instruments and a solid vocal cast featuring anthony 
rolfejohnson in the title role anne sofie von otter as his son 
idamante and the american soprano sylvia mcnair as ilia 
idamantes beloved 
idomeneo was paired with mozarts rarely performed last 
opera la clemenza di tito and both were recorded by deutsche 
grammophones archiv label 
idomeneo is scheduled for release next year still to come 
are fully staged productions in paris lisbon and amsterdam of 
the magic flute the marriage of figaro cosi fan 
tutte abduction from the seraglio and don giovanni 
compact disc and videotape recordings are planned 
the concert version of idomeneo was impeccably authentic 
the last performance of the opera in mozarts lifetime was a 
private concert directed by the composer in vienna in 1789 
according to constanze mozart idomeneo was her husbands 
favorite she recalled some years after his death that he had burst 
into tears during a private performance of the quartet in act 3 in 
which idamante sets off on my wanderings alone seeking death 
elsewhere until i find it 
idomeneo in gardiners estimation is the most 
passionately engaged of all the mozart operas unfailing in its 
inventiveness 
there is not a superfluous note or a gratuitous aria in it 
he said 
the conductor approaches mozart from nearly two centuries 
earlier through performances and recordings of works such as 
claudio monteverdis 1607 opera la favola dorfeo 
more recently the english baroque soloists recorded mozarts 
late symphonies and with malcolm bilson the piano concertos 
so we have done our apprenticeship as it were in mozarts 
instrumental and operatic style gardiner said during a break 
from rehearsing clemenza 
and the revelations are extraordinary from the moment you use 
these instruments because its not simply that the timbre of the 
individual instruments is so different from their modern 
equivalents but the sound is more visceral its more physical in 
a way and you feel that they are much more individual voices the 
instruments have a personality very very sharply defined so the 
mixing in with the voices is a fascinating process 
did they have to forget monteverdi to play mozart 
not a bit what you have to do is forget everything that you 
learned of later music music that comes after mozart gardiner 
said 
thats where the whole false performing tradition has grown 
up its seeing mozart as a precursor of the great operatic events 
of the 19th century where i feel we have gone wrong over mozart 
he said 
instead he regards mozart as the culmination of the baroque 
tradition from monteverdi through handel purcell and rameau 
gardiner made one surprising break with mozart tradition using 
a piano instead of a harpsichord with the recitatives mozart used 
a piano in opera certainly after 1782 gardiner says but thats a 
year after the premiere of idomeneo in munich 
in gardiners judgment a harpsichord simply sounds wrong it 
makes too abrupt a change from the orchestral playing 
he also parts company with some of the early instruments 
community on the matter of mozarts pupil franz xaver suessmayr 
so often maligned for his contributions to la clemenza di tito 
and the completion of the requiem 
the requiem especially has been drastically revised by modern 
editors but gardiner stuck with suessmayr for this summers 
performances of clemenza and the requiem 
i think he was not a very talented composer but he has the 
huge advantage of being a composer writing in the 1790s at the 
time when mozart was dying or dead and he is far closer to 
mozarts style than an awful lot of the editors and bigwigs who set 
themselves up as being neomozartean scholars gardiner said 
i have yet to come across an edition of the mozart requiem 
that is actually materially more convincing than that of suessmayr 
which certainly has its gaucheries and infelicities 
well we tidy up a little bit of it but some of the published 
versions that are now flaunted around even in the socalled 
authentic world are really a disgrace in terms of mozartean 
style 
</TEXT>
