<DOCNO> AP900626-0213 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here sits maggie the cat in a gray blouse and 
blue dress the real maggie the one tennessee williams had in mind 
when he wrote cat on a hot tin roof 
in her long speeches she has the vocal tricks of a priest 
delivering a liturgical chant williams writes of the plays 
feisty heroine the lines are almost sung always continuing a 
little beyond her breath so she has to gasp for another 
and lady st just the playwrights close friend for 35 years 
does speak quickly excitedly but in the polished throaty tones 
of british aristocracy not the drawl of the mississippi delta 
five oclock angel 2495 knopf is a collection of 
letters received from williams the title is the playwrights 
nickname for her with her own commentary woven throughout 
she was quick to criticize him whether dumping his memoirs in 
the garbage or scolding him for daydreaming too often but when it 
comes to defending tennessee williams no one is more determined 
than lady st just 
writing was his life she explained in an interview at her 
hotel suite in manhattan thats why people found him so 
difficult he was up there half the time he worked terribly hard 
look how prolific he was writing was his passion and he was my 
passion 
the daughter of a prominent surgeon she was born maria britneva 
in leningrad and moved to britain when she was still young she 
trained first for the ballet and then appeared in several plays for 
sir john gielguds production company in 1956 she married peter 
grenfell lord st just and had two daughters lord st just died 
in 1985 
she met williams in 1948 at a small party in london given by 
gielgud whose guests included laurence olivier vivien leigh and 
noel coward lady st just was 18 at the time and remembered 
spotting a shy little man one sock blue and the other red sitting 
nervously on the couch 
you felt this great sort of wave of fear she recalled of 
williams who had recently completed a streetcar named desire 
and would win the pulitzer prize for cat on a hot tin roof 
which was revived last year on broadway starring charles durning 
and kathleen turner 
i thought i must speak to him i thought he was an 
understudy i asked him if he would like a drink 
he seemed surprised i paid attention to him he looked up 
blushed and asked who brought you up my grandmother i said 
and he said my grandmother brought me up too only tennessee 
would ask a question like that 
so thanks appropriately to the kindness of a stranger their 
friendship began williams wrote her a month later and the letters 
continued until the last few months of his troubled life 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
lady st justs memories of williams who died in 1983 at age 
71 are of panicky opening nights long drives in rome visits with 
her family in england and the day when the playwright tossed her a 
finished script and told her to read it 
he said ive written the play about you he just flung the 
script at me i said tennessee how wonderful and then with 
mounting fury i read this play i said this is outrageous thats 
not me im from russia i want wolves i want carriages 
he said im writing about your spirituality your vitality 
you are life you know my children saw it and they kept laughing 
they said mommy youre just like that 
here are highlights from lady st justs discussion on the 
prizewinning play 
q in cat on a hot tin roof maggie says to brick her 
husband oh you weak beautiful people who give up with such 
grace is that how tennessee williams felt about himself 
a he never thought of himself as being weak not at all he was 
fragile not weak he was extremely strong and very determined and 
very positive theres this picture of tennessee as this kind of 
delicate person im trying to change that 
q but he was sensitive easily hurt 
a very but then he gave idiotic interviews himself i used to 
say if i write my memoirs i would call them oh do shut up 
tennessee i used to give him signals when he was doing 
interviews he used to just blab on and on and he would say things 
that were unnecessary and could be misinterpretated 
q in the mid1950s his letters make more and more references 
to his being depressed is that when you first noticed his problems 
a i think he always had problems but even when he was at his 
lowest he said en avant go forward he was so masculine you 
see he made decisions and took over he was incrdibly large in his 
attitude to me and he supported his sister his grandfather his 
mother his maiden aunt and many young writers and poets 
q flannery oconnor once wrote of one of her characters that 
she would have been a good person if she had somebody to hit her 
over the head all the time did williams value you for that 
a he needed somebody who was very truthful and terribly honest 
to a fault he knew i would never lie to him he taught me how not 
to lie but i was always very careful what i said about his plays 
and his poems i would step so far 
q what was the happiest you ever saw him 
a the happiest i ever saw him was when we were both doubled up 
in laughter playing the fools we shared the same sense of the 
ridiculous we would take a taxi on our way to the opening of a 
play and he was so nervous i would make him sing sing and do 
imitations he sung very very badly but he loved it 
q he didnt seem to trust many people 
a he was the most suspicious paranoid person it was a 
nightmare tennessee no one is looking at you 
we were on this plane once and we had this perfectly ordinary 
stewardess and he decided she was a murderess he wouldnt eat 
anything because he thought she had poisoned it he asked for a 
glass of water and ill never forget tenmnesee took a sip from 
the glass held it to me and said does this taste like water to 
you 
q in cat on a hot tin roof brick is always drinking and 
talks about getting the click in his head get the click and 
everything will be all right is that how williams felt 
a i think the click in his head was the click of the 
typewriter if he really got into a beautiful poem or a beautiful 
line that would be the click for him tennessee felt exactly the 
same way about his typewriter as brick did about his bottle 
</TEXT>
