the museum of modern art pays tribute to 
twentieth century fox this summer with a retrospective of over 90 
films made between 1935 and 1965 
opening july 1 twentieth century fox 19351965 traces 
three key decades in the history of the studio celebrating the 
talents of the artists on both sides of the cameras who shaped this 
period 
formed in 1915 the fox film corporation merged in 1935 with the 
much younger twentieth century to launch a major new studio 
the exhibition will highlight the epic biographies of the 1930s 
such as john fords the prisoner of shark island 1936 
also on exhibit will be a series of technicolor musicals 
developed during world war ii featuring such actresses as betty 
grable and carmen miranda 
the 50s segment shows how the studio maintained its preeminence 
with an entire new generation of stars epitomized by marilyn 
monroe and the introduction of cinemascope which literally 
changed the shape of motion pictures for years to come 
the retrospective runs through september 11 
