<TEXT>
ibm today launched its second assault on the 
home computer market a drive to tap the millions of americans it 
says want a home machine but have been scared by the technology 
the computers will be priced as low as 999 and in a departure 
for the worlds largest computer company will be sold at 
mainstream retailers such as sears roebuck and co dillards 
department stores and daytons department stores 
the machines were designed for people who have gained some 
knowledge of computers through their work but dont want to learn 
all the technical terms and concepts associated with them 
international business machines corp believes the potential 
audience is huge said skip gladfelter marketing manager for the 
new line 
we think there are millions of families sitting on the 
sidelines he said in an interview monday 
the computers called the personal system1 line will go on 
sale today in stores in the chicago dallasfort worth and 
minneapolisst paul areas ibm said the national rollout will 
come in september 
ibms first assault on the home market turned into a bitter 
failure production of the machines dubbed the pcjr was halted 
about a year and a half after they were launched in 1983 
pcjr was criticized for a toylike keyboard limited memory and a 
toosteep price 
this time around ibm executives say they plan to succeed their 
first step was to determine what went wrong with pcjr 
we all got phds in pcjr said robert amezcua product 
manager for the new ps1 line 
then a group of about 50 ibm employees in lexington ky began 
trying to figure out what consumers wanted gladfelter said 
since the fall of 1988 about 3000 consumers had a say in the 
new lines design through interviews and participation in focus 
groups he said 
among the features requested was ease of use a low price 
sufficient computing power to handle popular officecomputer 
software and availability at noncomputer stores he said 
like the more expensive macintosh from apple computer inc the 
ps1 line can be set up in minutes also like the mac the 
computers feature graphics and a handheld device called a mouse 
which manipulates an arrow onscreen to let users to chose the 
function they want to run 
the computers are built around the intel corp 80286 
microprocessor used in millions of office computers they also use 
the popular dos operating system making them compatible with 
thousands of applications programs for home and office use 
each machine contains a builtin modem which allows computers 
to hook up to distant computers or data services via phone lines 
one such service jointly owned by ibm and sears is prodigy it 
provides such things as home banking shopping and airline 
reservations the ps1 line contains a builtin program that 
provides an automatic linkup to prodigy 
the computers also include a popular software package from 
microsoft corp that combines a word processor a spreadsheet a 
database program and a communications program to run the modem 
the two cheapest ps1s lack a hard disc which is used to store 
many of the programs on the two highend models that means users 
of these models must insert a diskette containing the software 
after they turn on the machine on the more expensive models the 
programs automatically are pulled off the hard disc when the 
computers are turned on 
two of the models have blackandwhite screens while the other 
two offer color the most expensive model with a suggested retail 
price of 1999 has more memory in addition to the hard disc and 
color monitor 
all four machines feature fullsize keyboards but none has a 
printer which computer industry consultant sam albert said could 
be a drawback for some potential purchasers 
industry analysts say that although many families may want a 
home computer it may compete on a wish list with other expensive 
electronics devices such as camcorders laser disc players and 
largescreen tvs 
analysts also say ibm may have a rough time marketing the 
computers as consumer spending is declining due to economic 
uncertainty 
albert a former ibm executive said ibm may have solved the 
easeofuse problem but it still needs to show consumers why they 
need a home computer besides keeping up with the joneses 
