into this country said edward murphy president of the national 
music publishers association in new york 
a version of the dat recorder has been sold in japan and some 
parts of europe since 1987 and has been available through 
unofficial channels in the united states 
but manufacturers held back from launching the machines openly 
in this country because of a dispute over copying in a concession 
to record companies the manufacturers agreed to offer machines 
that can make only copies of cds not copies of copies 
sony became the first to offer popular priced recorders to 
american consumers friday matsushita electric industrial co the 
japanese firm that produces the panasonic technics and quasar 
brands hopes to have a competitively priced dat recorder in us 
stores by september a spokesman said 
sonys dtc75es priced at 950 includes circuitry that 
flags digital tapes copied from compact disc to prevent the 
tapes from being copied including that technology was part of an 
agreement between manufacturers and the recording industry that 
seemed to remove the threat of lawsuits from record companies 
but the accord and bills in the house and senate that would 
write the agreement into law did not resolve the festering issue 
of royalty payments for home taping 
george david weiss representing the copyright coalition told a 
senate subcommittee two weeks ago that the senate bill forces 
songwriters to give away copies of our music without payment of any 
kind 
murphy said his group was collecting information on the models 
available or soon to hit the us market to prepare for legal 
action 
we have several legal options we will pursue some form of 
legal remedy murphy said without elaborating 
the debate apparently didnt hamper sales in the first weekend 
i dont think people stormed the doors but it was generally 
very successful said shari haber spokeswoman for sony in park 
ridge nj 
manny couto sales manager at a sound advice store in miami 
said interest in the decks was tremendous 
it took our company which is represented in florida with 17 
stores three days to sell out of about 40 pieces couto said 
a lot of people bought a lot of people are looking 
in portland ore and seattle magnolia hifi was the only 
store to carry the dtc75es another version selling for about 50 
less the dtc700 will be available in more stores this week 
dave kaplan vice presidentpurchasing for magnolia said he 
sold onethird of his machines over the weekend without advertising 
we got off to a pretty good start with the dat machine 
kaplan said 
he would not say how many machines his store received calling 
it proprietary information magnolia sold the machines for 900 he 
said 
