<TEXT>
international lease finance corp 
the biggest us aircraft leaser has agreed to a 13 billion 
buyout by american international group inc to gain the financial 
backing of the insurance giant 
aig the largest us underwriter of commercial and industrial 
insurance also will provide ilfc with 125 million in financing as 
part of the deal 
analysts and spokesmen for the companies said the deal gives 
ilfc financial muscle at a time when it must borrow heavily to 
complete an ambitious expansion 
theyve found someone with lots of cash low cost of funds 
and willing to take some greater risk in return for greater 
rewards said daniel a hersch a securities analyst with bateman 
eichler hill richards inc in los angeles 
ilfc has grown strongly in recent years as airlines have relied 
more on leasing because of the high cost of and long wait for new 
aircraft purchases 
the company owns 98 jetliners worth more than 3 billion and 
averaging only three years of age 
it also has placed 10 billion worth of firm orders for planes 
to be delivered over 10 years and has another 4 billion in 
options that means ilfc which has had to borrow heavily and issue 
new stock to finance past deals will need much more capital at a 
time when it is harder to come by 
i think that having a strategic alliance with a backer of the 
stature and creditworthiness of aig should instill a greater 
confidence in the financial markets jay jacobsen a spokesman 
for ilfc said in a telephone interview from new york 
aigs triplea debt rating the highest possible will enable 
