<TEXT>
president bush has decided to impose long 
delays in offshore oil leasing off california and florida 
according to an administration official the white house was 
preparing an announcement later today 
the delay in granting new leases for offshore oil drilling would 
apply to one large area off south florida one region off southern 
california and one off northern california the offical said 
moratoriums of up to a decade would be imposed in most of the 
area under consideration said the official who spoke on condition 
of anonymity 
administration sources said earlier that bush wanted to 
forestall new oil drilling in those areas pending more study on 
potential impact to the environment 
the area covered by the decision includes a 67millionacre 
section of ocean off southern california 12 million acres off 
northern california and 13 million acres in the gulf of mexico 
near the florida everglades 
officials have said bush was leaning toward imposing the longest 
waiting period off the florida keys until the year 2002 or beyond 
bush named a task force last year headed by interior secretary 
manuel lujan to work with the national academy of sciences in 
studying the environmental impact of opening the three areas to new 
leasing 
the task force concluded that more study of the environmental 
effects was needed bush has repeatedly stated his wish to protect 
environmentally sensitive areas but also has said the nation 
should not have to depend on foreign oil 
bush postponed announcing a decision in the wake of a recent 
massive tanker spill off galveston texas a norwegian tanker was 
rocked by an explosion june 8 spilling 39 million gallons of oil 
it created a 30mile oil slick some 18 miles offshore most of it 
was skimmed off burned or evapaorated 
the entire florida congressional delegation and most of the 
california delegation have urged delays in new leasing republicans 
were especially sensitive to political fallout likely from any 
decision to open new oildrilling regions in an election year 
