<TEXT>
us and japanese negotiators tackled japanese 
pricing mechanisms and american shortfalls in savings and 
investment today as talks on structural trade problems moved into 
their second day 
although the talks originally were scheduled to end today they 
were continuing into the night and appeared likely to extend 
through wednesday 
us trade representative carla hills said in a speech monday to 
a washington trade conference sponsored by the institute for 
international economics it may be necessary to hold another round 
of talks on broad reforms to reduce japans 49 billion surplus in 
trade with the united states 
we will continue to talk until the job is done if there needs 
to be another meeting so be it she said 
hills warned there could be a backlash against japanese imports 
in the united states if the trade talks fail to expand foreign 
business opportunities in japan 
japan isnt open and until we get that parity of opportunity 
we will have an enormous buildup of antagonism that creates a 
backdrop for very bad public policy she said 
foreign ministry spokesman taizo watanabe said the talks were 
very intensive and he welcomed comments monday by us 
officials that the talks had been friendly and cooperative 
this underlines that our response has been very positive 
watanabe said 
nonetheless the two sides had failed to agree on the level to 
which japan would increase spending on public works 
watanabe said tuesdays session opened with a discussion of why 
japan tends to have higher prices than the united states on similar 
products 
in the afternoon he said the negotiators covered such problems 
on the us side as the government budget deficit low savings and 
investment rates excessive consumption low competitiveness of 
us products and poor training of us workers 
our position is that the us side also has some tasks he 
said 
such basic factors in the two countries economic systems are 
among many topics in the socalled structural impediments 
initiative talks launched last september japanese and us 
negotiators agreed on an interim report in april that both sides 
hailed as a strong step toward a final pact 
but since then washington has said tokyo was not following 
through fully on a pledge to increase public works spending and on 
tuesday japanese finance minister ryutaro hashimoto reportedly 
said washington apparently was ducking the problem of the huge us 
government budget deficit 
kyodo news service said hashimoto told reporters after a cabinet 
meeting that the united states had said in the interim report it 
would eliminate its budget deficit by 1993 but the pledge did not 
appear in washingtons draft of the final report 
later senior us officials said they had told the japanese 
side washington wants to look beyond eliminating the budget deficit 
by 1993 and to envision a budget surplus 
speaking on condition of anonymity they said there had been a 
good exchange of views tuesday but did not indicate whether 
agreements had been reached on any of the areas under discussion 
the us budget deficit is regarded as a spur to us 
consumption that increases demand for japanese imports and thus 
contributes to the trade imbalance at the same time us savings 
and investment levels are lower than japans that means greater 
modernization for japanese industry increasing its advantage in 
efficiency 
an increase in japanese public spending is expected to boost 
imports and soak up some savings the two countries disagreed over 
how high the increase should be with the americans asking for 500 
trillion yen or 322 trillion over the next 10 years japanese 
officials indicated they favored spending between 400 trillion and 
415 trillion yen or 258 trillion to 268 trillion 
among other things japan has agreed to ease restrictions on 
opening large retail stores revise land use policies to curb high 
land prices speed up processing of patent applications crack down 
on allegedly unfair business practices by corporate groups and 
open complicated pricing mechanisms all the measures are thought 
likely to increase foreign opportunities for trade and investment 
in japan 
