<TEXT>
trans world airlines inc plans to sell four 
jets by the end of the month cut back its flight schedule and end 
service to seven cities by oct 1 a top official told the 
airlines pilots 
in a letter to the members of the twa branch of the air line 
pilots association twa chief operating officer william hoar said 
the company cannot and will not allow twa to bleed to death 
left with no choice we can no longer delay our decision to 
either grow or downsize he said 
twa owner carl icahn has said in recent months he would shrink 
or dismantle the airline unless the pilots agreed to pay cuts and 
other concessions icahn has said he would modernize and expand the 
airline if the pilots agreed 
icahn has said that 10 percent pay cuts and other concessions 
would save the airline 80 million a year 
hoar said the moves were being forced by pilots resistance he 
said union leaders kent scott and bill compton had made misleading 
statements about twas financial condition to create panic in the 
ranks and build support for an employee buyout 
these ambitious pilots have decided that they want to control 
twa and will go to almost any length to attain that goal he 
wrote in the letter dated friday 
scott on tuesday called hoars comments ridiculous its 
pure fantasy and an obvious divisive tactic he said the pilots 
union had never been interested in buying the airline in its 
current financial situation 
twa whose hub is in st louis lost 2985 million last year 
largely because of burdensome interest payments on its 27 billion 
in debt the airline lost 143 million in the first three months of 
1990 
hoars letter said twa would end service to seven cities and 
reduce its flight schedule by 7 percent on oct 1 the seven cities 
have not yet been identified but scott said they probably would 
include nassau and freeport in the bahamas and syracuse ny 
hoar also said the airline would sell four jets two boeing 
747s one lockheed l1011 and one boeing 727 by the end of june 
at least four more boeing 727s will be sold in the next quarter he 
said 
twa previously had announced it was eliminating the two 747s and 
the l1011 from its fleet but didnt say when the 727s are among 
a group of 20 that the airline put on the market earlier this month 
hoar said twa still was trying to find buyers for the other 15 
727s he also confirmed that the airline was negotiating to sell 
gates and operating slots at laguardia airport in new york and 
national airport in washington dc 
twa will not need all of its gates and slots at those airports 
after it cuts back its flight operation in october he said 
this is not the direction i want to see twa going and more 
importantly it is not what has to be hoar wrote we can 
stabilize and grow this company together 
hoar said the company planned to obtain new jets to replace its 
old ones if the union would help reduce overhead and improve 
efficiency 
