<TEXT>
some 50 shareholders in t boone pickens private 
investment firm arrived tuesday to join the texas oilman and 
takeover strategist in his battle with the japanese business 
establishment 
officially the fight is for managerial control of koito 
manufacturing co an auto parts company affiliated with japans 
largest automaker toyota motor corp 
pickens firm boone co owns the largest share in koito and 
pickens has been demanding among other things a corresponding 
share of seats on its board of directors 
pickens and 52 other americans own 26 percent of koitos 16036 
million outstanding shares they will face their japanese 
counterparts thursday in an annual shareholders meeting at koitos 
headquarters in central tokyo 
the fight has come to symbolize to some americans the trials 
faced by investors in japan at a time when many japanese companies 
are buying us businesses and property 
the clash also reflects fundamental differences in how americans 
and japanese conduct business and accumulate wealth it is one of 
the cases raised by some us officials in urging japan to reform 
its economic policies to encourage more foreign trade and 
investment 
in current talks on reforms in both economies japan has 
promised to crack down on collusive business practices conducted by 
keiretsu 
keiretsu are corporate families bound by mutual shareholdings 
and other financial ties and by cooperative business strategies 
many japanese believe that keiretsu are crucial to japans entire 
justintime system of production and supply in which parts are 
delivered as needed not stockpiled into costly inventories 
koito belongs to the keiretsu surrounding toyota the auto 
company is its second largest shareholder after boone co with 
about 20 percent of koitos shares it also buys about half the 
auto lighting equipment koito sells 
critics such as pickens say the keiretsu tend to exclude 
outsiders especially foreigners they also say the bigname 
companies at the top of the manufacturing pyramid squeeze their 
smaller subcontractors mercilessly and deprive shareholders of 
their fair share of profits 
while americans have acquired a taste for many japanese 
products keiretsu is one thing we will never accept pickens 
told reporters tuesday 
of course there are people who claim that keiretsu are a 
major part of japanese culture and that the rest of the world 
should just accept it he said i disagree a keiretsu is a 
cartel is a cartel is a cartel whatever you call it its wrong 
pickens says he resorted to a public campaign against koitos 
management after top executives of koito toyota and other major 
japanese firms refused to meet with him or accept his proposals 
give me a chance is that an unusual request he said 
take me to the backroom i cant get into the backroom he 
added responding to suggestions that he take a less 
confrontational approach in dealing with japanese business 
koito officials accuse pickens of acting as a front for japanese 
investor kitaro watanabe who they say has twice tried to greenmail 
them 
greenmailers buy large amounts of a companys stock in an effort 
to force the company to buy the shares back at a premium to 
maintain control 
pickens does not deny he may have a relationship with watanabe 
but he refuses to disclose any details of the financing involved in 
his purchase of the koito shares from watanabe 
shareholders on thursday will vote on pickens request for four 
seats on koitos 20member board and his proposals for an 
antigreenmail resolution an annual statement on whether koito has 
engaged in anticompetitive activities an annual shareholder vote 
on salary and retirement benefits of board members an annual 
report on pricing policies a further increase in the dividend and 
an accounting of what pickens suggests amounts to an illegal slush 
fund 
pickens said he had received proxies from more than half of 
individual koito shareholders who hold a total of about 4 million 
shares in the company indicating support for his proposals 
koitos board has rejected all pickens proposals as unnecessary 
</TEXT>
