<TEXT>
japanese and us officials agreed to extend trade 
talks after failing tuesday to reach final agreement on substantial 
economic changes aimed at narrowing the trade imbalance between the 
countries 
the meetings originally were scheduled to end tuesday were 
extended as negotiators struggled to resolve differences over 
specific strategies to dismantle structural trade barriers 
we would have to be extremely efficient to finish the talks 
wednesday a senior japanese official said speaking anonymously 
we have received many comments from the us side on the contents 
of our report and will have to work on it 
on tuesday second day of the talks us and japanese 
negotiators discussed japanese pricing mechanisms and american 
shortfalls in savings and investment that hurt the competitiveness 
of us industries 
us officials at the talks said they explained efforts to 
tackle the us federal budget deficit which is seen as one reason 
for a shortfall in investment in us industry 
the officials who spoke on condition of anonymity said they 
told the japanese that washington wants to look beyond eliminating 
the budget deficit by 1993 and to envision a budget surplus 
officials on both sides described the discussions as cooperative 
nonetheless at the end of two days of intensive talks the two 
sides failed to reach agreement on any of the areas under 
discussion including the level of japans spending on public 
works officials said 
public spending and other basic economic policies are among many 
topics in the socalled structural impediments initiative talks 
launched last year 
japanese and us negotiators agreed on an interim report in 
april that both sides said represented major progress they have 
since been finetuning a final report on the talks 
on tuesday officials first discussed reasons why japan tends to 
have higher prices than the united states on similar products 
they later dealt with problems on the us side including the 
budget deficit low savings and investment rates excessive 
consumption low competitiveness of us products and poor training 
of us workers 
our position is that the us side also has some tasks 
foreign ministry spokesman taizo watanabe said 
officials said they were still debating japans proposals on 
easing restrictions on opening large retail stores revising land 
use policies to curb high real estate prices speeding up 
processing of patent applications cracking down on allegedly 
unfair business practices by corporate groups and simplifying 
complicated pricing mechanisms all the measures are thought likely 
to increase foreign opportunities for trade and investment in japan 
the most difficult issue however was expected to be tokyos 
plan to boost spending on public infrastructure such as roads 
parks and sewers an increase in such spending is expected to boost 
imports of construction products and counter japans high savings 
rate 
