<DOCNO> AP900626-0252 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
motorola inc said tuesday it plans to build a 
satellitebased cellular phone system that will connect users with 
telephones anywhere in the world 
the system could supplement conventional phone service in 
nations where it is poor such as in eastern europe and provide 
mobile phone service in rural areas where it is not offered 
motorola officials said 
target users include traveling business people passengers of 
ships and aircraft disasterrelief workers and residents of 
underdeveloped nations 
the system called iridium would use a network of 77 satellites 
that would receive calls from handheld telephones resembling 
todays cellular phones the phones would cost as low as 3000 
compared with about 400 for todays cheapest cellular phones 
motorola said 
the electronics company said it would launch test satellites in 
1992 and expected full service to be available as soon as 1996 
we see the potential of iridium as nothing short of 
revolutionary john f mitchell a motorola vice chairman told 
reporters at a news conference 
but the system faces several obstacles motorola needs 
regulatory approval to operate the satellites from various 
government groups worldwide it also must come up with the 23 
billion it says it will cost to build the system 
motorola says it wants to take on four or five partners that 
each would provide funding in exchange for a stake in the venture 
in addition it is envisioned that several of these partners would 
be satellite operators that already have the necessary government 
operating authority 
the partners have not been selected but motorola said it has 
signed agreements with three satellite operators to explore 
constructing the system american mobile satellite corp of 
washington dc international maritime satellite organization of 
london and telesat mobile inc of canada 
these three satellite groups may become partners in iridium 
said durrell w hillis a motorola vice president who heads the 
satellite effort 
motorola also said it is negotiating with other potential 
partners including great britains principal phone company 
british telecommunications plc and organizations in australia 
hong kong and japan 
iridium would be connected to existing phone networks however 
customers probably would not want to use iridium phones to make 
local cellular calls in areas served by existing groundbased 
systems because the cost per iridium call would be much greater 
hillis said 
in addition iridium phones would not be compatible with 
existing or planned groundbased cellular phone networks so users 
could not tap into these networks directly by bypassing the 
expensive satellite system 
as a result iridium customers probably would need to carry two 
cellular phones while traveling that could provide a huge 
potential new market for motorola which already is the worlds 
largest maker of cellular phones 
the schaumburg illbased company also would make the 
communications gear for the satellites and the computerized control 
sytstems that would operate them 
hillis said motorola knows of no other similar system in the 
works 
john pemberton an analyst with the research firm gartner group 
of stamford conn said american telephone amp telegraph co is 
believed to be working on plans for a satellitebased cellular 
phone system that would use two giant satellites fixed in position 
over the earth the iridium satellites would orbit the planet 
pemberton said he was impressed with motorolas plans and called 
them achievable however he said he believed the system would need 
more than 77 satellites to provide sufficient capacity 
the iridium system under development since late 1987 would 
operate like a cellular phone network in the sky passing calls 
from one to the other as do the transmission towers located in each 
cell of a groundbased cellular phone network 
the satellites would be located 413 nautical miles above the 
earth considered a low orbit for satellites the low orbit would 
allow the use of small handheld phones with tiny antennas rather 
than the satellite dishes required to beam signals to existing 
satellites 
the satellites would pass a call around the globe to the 
intended recipient if the recipient has an iridium phone he would 
receive the call directly otherwise the call would connect with a 
conventional landbased phone system to be completed 
each iridium user would be given a personal telephone number 
for someone to reach a user they would simply dial the number and 
would not have to know the users location motorola said 
iridium named after the 77th element on the periodic table 
would not have the capacity to replace conventional cellular phone 
systems in urban areas hillis said 
motorola has extensive experience in satellite and outerspace 
communications it made the communications equipment for every us 
space mission hillis said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

