sonat inc has agreed to pay 3005 
million to settle claims stemming from a 1989 fire that killed 
seven people and destroyed a production platform operated by arco 
oil and gas co off the louisiana coast officials said 
arco announced the settlement monday a sonat spokesman 
confirmed that the birminghambased company had reached an 
agreement in principal to settle all claims against sonat and 
litigation involving the fire on march 19 1989 
an april report released by the minerals management service 
us coast guard and office of pipeline safety said a number of 
factors led to the accident according to the oil amp gas journal 
problems began in february 1989 when an anchor ruptured a sonat 
pipeline in repairing the damage and clearing the pipeline the 
report said the pipeline released a mix of gas liquid 
hydrocarbons and water 
in march the mixture ignited and spread to an arco facility 
platform baker located 20 miles southeast of venice la the 
flames caused an explosion that reached an adjacent platform 
connected by a 50foot causeway 
of the 42 people on the rig five arco workers and two contract 
employees died another 10 workers were injured platform baker 
suffered extensive damage while the second platform was slightly 
damaged 
arco which also was forced to halt production of 18000 barrels 
of oil a day sued sonat two subsidiaries and a contractor in 
april 1989 
