<TEXT>
a house subcommittee voted tuesday to give 
federal judges more discretion to dismiss as frivolous some civil 
suits under the nations antiracketeering laws 
on a unanimous vote the judiciary committees 10member 
subcommittee on crime approved legislation that would narrow the 
definition of racketeering in civil suits to exclude ordinary 
commercial disputes and contract cases 
ordinary businessmen are being branded as racketeers simply 
because they have become embroiled in a commercial dispute said 
rep frederick boucher dva the bills chief sponsor 
the bill would revise the 1970 racketeer influence and corrupt 
organizations act rico to effectively deny plaintiffs in many 
civil suits the ability to recover triple they amount of damages 
they incurred 
under the legislation a judge would be required to dismiss a 
civil rico suit if a defendant had not been convicted of criminal 
racketeering or if the judge could not find that triple damages 
were warranted because of the magnitude of the injuries 
boucher called the current statute one of the most abused 
provisions of federal law having made its way into domestic 
disputes between spouses inheritance disputs among family members 
disagreements among church members and litigation involving 
landlords and tenants 
the bill would apply the new proposed gatekeeper provisions 
retroactively to some 1500 currently pending civil suits on a 64 
vote the committee defeated an amendment by rep john conyers 
dmich to deny retroactivity 
supporters of the failed amendment said it was needed to 
preserve the rico suit of some 23000 bondholders who lost 200 
million in the parent company of lincoln savings and loan 
association against the thrifts owner phoenix financier charles 
h keating jr and his associates 
given the inherent ambiguities in the gatekeeper provision 
there is no assurance that a judge will not later on deprive my 
clients of a meritorious verdict the bondholders attorney 
william lerach said in a letter to the subcommittee 
to give charles keating and ferdinand marcos another bite of 
the apple is ridiculous said subcommittee member chuck douglas 
rnh referring to another suit now pending against the estate of 
the deceased former dictator of the philippines 
making the changes retroactive also was opposed by the state 
attorneys general and state insurance commissioners 
the senate judiciary committee last january removed a 
retroactivity provision from a similar bill written by sen dennis 
deconcini dariz one of five senators under investigation by the 
senate ethics committees over their involvement with keating 
rather than give judges more discretion to dismiss civil rico 
suits the senate bill would simply eliminate triple damages except 
in cases brought by the government 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

