<TEXT>
the former chairman and three top executives 
of midwest federal savings and loan were indicted tuesday on 
federal fraud and conspiracy charges involving financial losses 
sustained by the failed thrift 
us attorney general dick thornburgh announced the 40count 
indictment returned by a federal grand jury 
this indictment is a further demonstration of our 
determination to pursue serious allegations against savings and 
loan ripoff artists across the united states thornburgh said 
midwest federal which had assets of 35 billion is being 
liquidated by the government at an expected cost of 1 billion the 
thrift was about 1 billion in debt when it was seized by 
regulators in february 1989 
indicted were chairman harold w greenwood jr charlotte e 
masica former executive vice president and managing officer 
donald j snede former senior vice president and chief financial 
officer and robert a mampel former executive assistant to the 
chairman 
resolution trust corp the federal agency created to bail out 
the nations failing thrifts put midwest up for sale in april the 
sampl has 30 branches in minnesota nine in iowa eight in oklahoma 
and two in california 
greenwood mampel masica and greenwoods daughter former 
midwest federal vice president susan greenwood olson were ousted 
when the savings and loan was declared insolvent and seized by 
regulators 
greenwood olson was indicted in march on 10 fraud counts 
involving 15 million in loans to the jockey club marina and resort 
in miami prosecutors allege the loans far exceeded the value of 
the resort and that false documents were drafted to hide mdwest 
federals shaky financial condition 
much of tuesdays indictment centered on midwest federals ties 
with green tree acceptance inc a st paulbased company that 
finances mobile homes 
in early 1987 greenwood masica and snede hid from regulators a 
47 million shortfall in finance income expected from a 15 
billion portfolio of mobile home loans the indictment alleges 
midwest had purchased the loan service rights to the portfolio from 
green tree for 188 million 
the executives also inflated the thrifts net worth and made 
unsound loans to delinquent borrowers to avoid writeoffs so as to 
preserve their bonuses the indictment said 
the indictment also charges the four with misapplying funds to 
pay for personal airline flights and club memberships and to pay 
excessive levels of compensation to themselves and lend 
themselves money without proper approval 
regulators say deposits at midwest federal have dropped 10 
percent since the takeover as of may 31 the thrifts retail 
deposits were about 19 billion 
gov rudy perpich has tried to distance himself from greenwood 
who was one of perpichs biggest campaign contributors before the 
sampl collapsed the democratic governor was granted use of midwests 
corporate jet and perpich had appointed greenwood to the 
metropolitan airports commission and the greater minnesota corp 
board 
perpich said monday he had no business dealings with midwest and 
that the state does not regulate savings and loans 
william mauzy attorney for greenwood said the indictment was 
a republican prosecutors attempt to blame a high profile 
democrat he said greenwoods actions were never fraudulent 
</TEXT>
